## Where to contribute for maximum visibility and career impact

The strategic insight from successful open-source contributors is counterintuitive: **target medium-sized, rapidly growing projects (5K–30K stars) where you can become a top-5 contributor within one to two months**, rather than drowning in massive repos where PRs languish for weeks. The career value of "top contributor to a tool used by Fortune 500 companies" on a resume is transformational.

**Pydantic AI** (`pydantic/pydantic-ai`, ~15,500 stars) is the #1 recommendation. It's the goldilocks zone — rapidly growing but not yet massive, hitting v1.0 in late 2025. Built by the Pydantic team whose validation layer underpins OpenAI's SDK, Anthropic's SDK, LangChain, LlamaIndex, and CrewAI, it offers a "FastAPI feeling for AI applications" that directly leverages your FastAPI expertise. It now supports the A2A protocol, MCP, durable execution, and 25+ model providers. Documentation, new model provider integrations, and example agents are all areas needing work.

**The MCP Python SDK** (`modelcontextprotocol/python-sdk`) ranks second. Contributing to the protocol itself — not just building on it — is an extraordinary signal to employers. The spec has had three revisions in 2025 alone, and the registry marketplace is actively seeking new server implementations. Build a novel MCP server, improve SDK documentation, or add examples to reference servers.

**LangGraph** (`langchain-ai/langgraph`, ~24,800 stars) is the natural third choice given your existing LangChain experience. The LangChain contributing guide explicitly welcomes new contributors and maintains "good first issue" labels. Focus on the `langchain-community` package for third-party integrations rather than core — these PRs face less competition and review faster.

Beyond the top three: **CrewAI** (45,900 stars) needs MCP server integrations and streaming improvements. **smolagents** from Hugging Face has a codebase of roughly 1,000 lines — small enough to fully understand — and carries the reputational weight of the HuggingFace brand. **LiteLLM** (34,000 stars) constantly needs new LLM provider integrations as providers emerge. **Instructor** by Jason Liu is smaller but essential for structured extraction pipelines and values documentation PRs.

One critical update: **avoid AutoGen**. Microsoft merged it with Semantic Kernel into the unified Microsoft Agent Framework in October 2025. AutoGen now receives only bug fixes and security patches.

The proven PR strategy: start with documentation fixes (merged fastest, builds goodwill), progress to bug fixes with tests, then tackle feature PRs. Keep PRs under 50 lines — large PRs get procrastinated on or closed. Join the project's Discord first, answer questions for a week or two, and maintainers will remember you favorably when reviewing your code. A 90-day plan of 5–10 merged PRs across 2–3 repos, with at least one substantial feature contribution, transforms a GitHub profile from "tutorials completed" to "production contributor."

