## Your portfolio should prove you can ship production systems

The data is unambiguous: **87% of hiring managers** consider portfolios more valuable than resumes for assessing technical skills, and **84%** specifically want to see working applications rather than just code repositories. For AI/ML engineers, the bar is higher — Kaggle competitions and MNIST classifiers no longer differentiate.

The dominant tech stack for developer portfolios in 2026 is **Next.js + TypeScript + Tailwind CSS + Framer Motion**, deployed on Vercel. For an AI/ML engineer who wants to embed interactive demos, Next.js provides the full-stack capability to serve live model inference alongside static content. Alternatively, **Astro** (ships zero JavaScript by default) excels for content-heavy portfolios with integrated blogs. Use MDX for blog posts — Markdown with embedded JSX components for visualizations and demos. Secure `rahulmodugula.dev` or `rahulmodugula.ai` as your domain.

Structure the portfolio with **five focused sections**: a hero with a clear value proposition ("I build production multi-agent AI systems"), three to five flagship projects with live demos and architecture diagrams, a technical blog with deep-dives, a skills section organized by category (Languages, AI Frameworks, MLOps, Cloud), and contact links. Each project page should tell a narrative: problem, approach, technical decisions and trade-offs, quantified results. Include screenshots, architecture diagrams, and GIFs — hiring managers rarely run your code.

The specific differentiator for AI engineers is **interactive demos embedded directly in the portfolio**. Gradio and Streamlit widgets can serve live model inference. Embed data visualizations with Plotly or D3.js. Show the full deployment pipeline: Docker containers, CI/CD, monitoring dashboards. The projects that impress most demonstrate end-to-end thinking: data pipeline through model training through evaluation through production deployment through monitoring.

For your GitHub profile, create a profile README with a professional intro, current focus, and tech stack badges. Pin six repositories — vary them across multi-agent systems, RAG, MCP, and infrastructure. Each pinned repo needs a comprehensive README with architecture diagrams, setup instructions, and live demo links. Maintain weekly commit activity; consistent green squares signal active development even when the contributions are small documentation improvements.

