## A concrete 90-day execution plan

The path from Virginia Tech senior to top-tier AI engineer candidate requires shipping publicly, contributing visibly, and building community — all simultaneously. Here is the prioritized sequence.

**Weeks 1–2**: Launch your portfolio site on `rahulmodugula.dev` using Next.js + Tailwind + MDX, deployed on Vercel. Optimize your GitHub profile README with pinned repos, tech stack badges, and a clear professional identity. Set up a Substack newsletter. Join the LangChain, Hugging Face, and Anthropic Discord servers and begin answering questions daily.

**Weeks 3–6**: Ship your flagship project — the multi-agent code review system with Graph RAG and MCP integration is the strongest option. Document it obsessively with architecture diagrams, design decision explanations, and a live demo. Publish your first three Substack posts: a multi-agent LangGraph tutorial, an MCP server implementation walkthrough, and a RAG evaluation practical guide. Create Twitter threads for each and cross-post to Dev.to.

**Weeks 7–10**: Begin open-source contributions to Pydantic AI and the MCP Python SDK. Start with documentation PRs to build goodwill, then progress to bug fixes and small features. Ship a second portfolio project — an MCP-native research agent or evaluation platform. Submit a talk proposal to the AI Engineer conference or a local meetup.

**Weeks 11–13**: Aim to have 5–10 merged PRs across two to three repos. Publish weekly on Substack with consistent Twitter distribution. Share project milestones on r/LocalLLaMA and r/MachineLearning. By this point, your GitHub profile should show a flagship project with real stars, contributions to recognized repos, and a consistent commit graph.

The engineers who reach the 0.1% don't get there through credentials alone. They get there by shipping real tools that other engineers use, writing about what they learn with specificity and depth, and showing up in communities with genuine helpfulness. Your stack is already positioned at the center of the highest-demand area in software engineering. The remaining variable is execution velocity — how fast you can convert what you know into public, visible, production-grade work that speaks for itself.





